\section*{Relevant Experience}
\vspace{-10pt}
\begin{longtable}{r| R}
2013 -- Current & {\bf Graduate Teaching Assistant}\\
                & Department of Statistics\\
                & West Virginia University, WV\\
                & {\bf Courses:}\\
                & Elementary Statistical Inference, Understanding
                  Statistics\\
                & {\bf Responsibilities:}\\
                & I teach and grade for laboratory sections of undergraduate Statistics
                courses where the students review concepts and get hands-on experience
                using Statistics to solve realistic
                problems. I also work in our Statistics Tutoring
                Center to help students master 
                coursework from any of our department's courses, from 100- to
                400-level, in a one-on-one environment.\\
&\\
2014 -- Current & {\bf Graduate Research Assistant}\\
               & The West Virginia Dialect Project\\
               & West Virginia University, WV\\
               & {\bf Responsibilities:}\\
               & This position involved working with linguists to process
                 phonetic, phonological, and social data and develop statistical
                 models in the complex task of describing sociolinguistic variation 
                 in the Appalachian Speech Community\\

\end{longtable}
\newpage
\begin{longtable}{r| R}
2014 -- Current & {\bf Graduate Research Assistant}\\
                & Department of Statistics\\
                & West Virginia University, WV\\
                & {\bf Responsibilities:}\\
                & I worked with faculty in the Data Sciences program to 
                  develop high quality content for online courses that meet
                  the standards set by the Quality Matters rubric and the
                  Southern Regional Education Board.\\
&\\
2010 -- 2013  & \bf{Research Assistant}\\
             & \bf{The Lexomics Project}\\
             & California University of Pennsylvania, PA\\
             & \bf{Responsibilities:}\\
             & The goal of this project was to use Machine Learning techniques
               to analyze Medieval Latin and Old English manuscripts for 
               stylistic variation.  I was responsible for preparing data
               for processing, devoping analysis software, and explaining
               our methods in journal articles and presentation as part of an 
               interdisciplinary team of experts in several fields.\\ 
&\\
Summer 2012 & \bf{Research Intern}\\
            & \bf{The Wheaton Lexomics Group}\\
            & Wheaton College, MA\\
            & \bf{Responsibilities:}\\
            & As a research intern, I worked directly with
            statisticians and computer scientists to develop software
            and techniques to identify which language features are most 
            indicative of stylistic variation in natural language.\\

&\\
2011 -- 2013  & \bf{Undergraduate Student Assistant}\\
             & Department of Mathematics and Computer Science\\
             & California University of Pennsylvania\\
             & \bf{Courses:}\\
             & College Trigonometry, Elementary Topics in
               Math, Fundamentals of Math, 
               Pre-Calculus, Problem Solving and Programming Constructs,
               Introduction to Programming\\
             & \bf{Responsibilities:}\\
             & I helped professors in Math and Computer Science lecture,
             prepare coursework, proctor exams, and assess student
             work. I also ran an instructional lab for tutoring 
             individual and groups of students who needed extra help.\\
\end{longtable}

